 FEATURE n. 1. A surprising property of a program. Occasionally docu- mented.
To call a property a feature sometimes means the author of the program did
not consider the particular case, and the program makes an unexpected,
although not strictly speaking an incorrect response. see BUG. "That's not a
bug, that's a feature!" A bug can be changed to a feature by documenting it.
2. A well-known and beloved property; a facility. Sometimes features are
planned, but are called crocks by others. An approximately correct spectrum:
(These terms are all used to describe programs or portions thereof, except
for the first two, which are included for completeness.) CRASH STOPPAGE BUG
SCREW LOSS MISFEATURE CROCK KLUGE HACK WIN FEATURE PERFECTION (The last is
never actually attained.)